[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1028[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1029[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1030[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1031[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1032[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1033[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Bedrock (Agents, Knowledge Bases, Guardrails, foundation model with strong tool-use, embedding model), Amazon OpenSearch Serverless, AWS HealthLake, AWS Lambda, AWS Step Functions, Amazon API Gateway, AWS WAF, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, AWS KMS (with separate keys per sensitive-data class), AWS Secrets Manager, Amazon CloudWatch, AWS CloudTrail, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, Amazon Pinpoint, Amazon Connect, Amazon QuickSight, Amazon MSK or Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (HL7 ingestion). Optionally: Amazon SageMaker (custom seam-detection model hosting). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1034[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **External Inputs** | Cross-organizational data integration: HL7 v2 ADT, ORU, SIU feeds from participating hospitals; FHIR APIs for ambulatory and inpatient data from participating EHRs; HIE and TEFCA QHIN integration where the institution participates; payer claims-feed integration where the institution has a value-based-care or claims-data partnership; pharmacy data via NCPDP standards or pharmacy-network APIs; home-health visit notes via vendor APIs; lab feeds via HL7 ORU; scheduled-appointment feeds from connected scheduling systems. Coordination-protocol corpus curated and version-controlled by clinical leadership including transition-of-care protocols (hospital-to-home, hospital-to-SNF, ED-to-PCP, ambulatory-procedure recovery), referral-tracking protocols, post-discharge protocols, post-procedure protocols, medication-reconciliation protocols, condition-specific coordination playbooks. Patient-education content library reviewed by clinical leadership and patient-experience leadership, multilingual and multi-reading-level. Validated translations reviewed by language-services team and clinical leadership. Care-team workforce capacity (employed or contracted nurse care managers, social workers, pharmacists, care coordinators) sized to expected escalation volume. 988 Suicide and Crisis Lifeline routing integration. Institutional crisis-line integration. Care-navigation and social-services integration. Mandatory-reporting-pathway integration. Consent-management integration with state-specific privacy compliance. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1035[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Per-Lambda least-privilege roles. Integration adapter Lambdas have read access only to their respective external sources and write access only to the coordination-state and provenance-journal tables. The protocol-retrieve Lambda has read access to the protocol corpus only. The seam-detection-rule-engine Lambda has read access to the coordination state and write access to the seam-flags registry. The care-team-alert-propose Lambda has write access to the alert queue. The escalation-propose Lambda has invocation permission for the escalation Step Functions workflow. None of the assistant's Lambdas have write access to external clinical records except for institutionally-approved coordination-event records (e.g., FHIR Communication resources for the conversation log; FHIR CarePlan annotations for coordination notes where the institution permits; with explicit consent and clinical-leadership approval). Resource-based policies pin invoking principals to the production agent and API Gateway stage ARNs. Cross-account access for multi-organization data integration uses AWS Resource Access Manager and named cross-account roles with named operational ownership. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1036[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA and Compliance** | AWS BAA signed. Verify all services in scope are HIPAA-eligible at build time. The assistant is patient-facing PHI with cross-organizational data flow. The institutional regulatory team reviews the data-sharing posture against the Information Blocking rule, state-specific privacy regulations, 42 CFR Part 2 for substance-use treatment data where applicable, state-specific mental-health-record statutes where applicable, state-specific HIV-record statutes where applicable, state-specific genetic-test-result statutes where applicable, and state-specific minor-confidentiality protections where applicable. The institutional regulatory team reviews the FDA-strategy positioning before launch and on each material scope change; cross-organizational coordination assistants with clinical-recommendation features may sit on the FDA SaMD line. The institutional malpractice insurer is part of the policy review. State-specific regulations on AI-mediated patient communication, on caregiver-proxy access, and on cross-organizational data sharing may apply. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory landscape for cross-organizational care-coordination software includes HIPAA, the ONC Information Blocking and Interoperability rules under the 21st Century Cures Act, state medical-record statutes, state caregiver-consent and proxy-access laws, 42 CFR Part 2, and FDA SaMD framework where applicable; specific obligations vary --> |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1037[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | Coordination state, provenance journal, referral lifecycle, transition-of-care store, seam-flags registry, conversation archive, decision-record journal, patient-education library, protocol corpus: SSE-KMS with customer-managed keys. Sensitive-record categories (42 CFR Part 2, mental-health, HIV, genetic): SSE-KMS with separately-managed customer keys for blast-radius containment, with strict access-control surfaces. S3 archives: Object Lock in compliance mode for the retention window. DynamoDB tables: customer-managed KMS at rest, with sensitive-category tables on separate keys. Lambda environment variables: KMS-encrypted. Secrets Manager: customer-managed KMS. TLS in transit for all AWS API calls and all integrations with external systems. Cross-organizational data-in-transit posture documented per integration partner. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1038[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: integration-adapter Lambdas (HL7 listener, FHIR consumer, claims-feed processor, pharmacy-API consumer, vendor-API consumers) run in VPC with controlled egress per partner. PrivateLink or VPN to partner-hosted endpoints where supported; tightly-scoped NAT path with allow-list otherwise. Tool Lambdas that call HealthLake, EHR, care-team workflows, and care-navigation systems run in VPC. VPC endpoints for DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch Logs, EventBridge, Bedrock, OpenSearch Serverless, HealthLake, Step Functions, Pinpoint, Connect, MSK or Kinesis Data Streams, and SageMaker (where used). The patient-facing edge is public; the back-office and integration traffic is private. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1039[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled with data events on all sensitive S3 buckets (audit-archive, decision-record-journal, provenance-archive, protocol-corpus, patient-education-library) and DynamoDB tables (coordination-state, provenance-journal, referral-lifecycle, transition-of-care, seam-flags-registry, caregiver-access-store, consent-record-store, decision-record-journal, etc.), Secrets Manager secrets, and customer-managed KMS keys. Bedrock and Bedrock Agents invocations logged. Lambda invocations logged. API Gateway access logs enabled. Step Functions execution logs enabled. MSK or Kinesis Data Streams data events logged. Connect interactions logged with appropriate retention. CloudTrail logs in a dedicated S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode. Audit retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, state-specific medical-record retention rules, and FDA SaMD post-market obligations where applicable. Cross-organizational data-access events specifically tracked for Information Blocking rule reporting. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1040[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic patient profiles stratified by chronic-condition mix, by transition-of-care setting, by language, by socioeconomic context, by caregiver profile (no caregiver, single caregiver, multi-caregiver), by integration coverage (well-instrumented, partially-instrumented, poorly-instrumented). Synthetic care-team profiles spanning multi-organization scenarios. Synthetic conversation histories covering long-running coordination engagement, attrition patterns, sensitive disclosures, seam-detection-triggered conversations, transition-of-care episodes, referral lifecycles. Validated coordination-protocol corpus reviewed by clinical leadership. Validated patient-education content library. Validated translations of all patient-facing content reviewed by language-services team and clinical leadership. Test EHR, HIE, payer-claims, pharmacy, home-health, and care-navigation systems with synthetic data. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1041[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | At a mid-sized payer or accountable-care-organization scale (50,000 active engaged members; average 1-3 conversational engagements per week per active member; average 4-10 turns per engagement; average 3,000 tokens of prompt and 500 tokens of response per turn for the orchestration model plus tool-call overhead; plus continuous integration-layer ingestion for all members): Bedrock LLM invocations typically $3-10 per active member per month for a Sonnet-class orchestration model, totaling approximately $1.8M-6M per year. Bedrock Agents and Knowledge Bases hosting plus the OpenSearch Serverless retrieval indices typically $80,000-300,000 per year. Lambda, API Gateway, WAF, DynamoDB, S3, KMS, Secrets Manager, CloudWatch, CloudTrail, EventBridge, Kinesis Firehose, Glue, Athena, Step Functions, MSK or Kinesis Data Streams total approximately $200,000-700,000 per year combined (cross-organizational integration adds substantial Lambda and DynamoDB volume). AWS HealthLake typically $80,000-400,000 per year (cost varies substantially with data volume, FHIR resource mix, and HL7 ingestion volume). Pinpoint typically $30,000-150,000 per year. Connect for warm-handoff queue and care-manager routing typically $80,000-400,000 per year (cost varies substantially with handoff volume and care-manager staffing model). SageMaker (when used for custom seam-detection models) typically $30,000-120,000 per year. Total AWS infrastructure typically $2.4M-8.5M per year at this scale (approximately $4-14 per active member per month, with substantial variability based on integration coverage and conversation volume). The care-management workforce cost (employed or contracted nurse case managers, pharmacists, social workers) and the cross-organizational data-exchange partnership costs (HIE participation fees, TEFCA QHIN access, claims-data partnership fees, pharmacy-network API fees) are typically larger than the AWS infrastructure cost combined and are the dominant operational expenses. <!-- TODO: replace with verified pricing once the implementing team validates against the AWS Pricing Calculator; specific costs depend on Bedrock model choice, conversation volume, integration breadth, FHIR-source choice, and channel mix --> |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1042[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1043[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1044[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1045[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1046[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1047[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Bedrock** | LLM for orchestration and conversational response generation; embedding model for the protocol corpus, patient-education library, and conversation history |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1048[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Bedrock Agents** | Tool orchestration: define coordination tools as action groups, manage the multi-step LLM-and-tool flow |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1049[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases** | Managed RAG over (a) coordination-protocol corpus, (b) patient-education library, (c) longitudinal conversation history. Metadata-filtered retrieval (protocol type, transition type, condition, audience, language, reading level, version, effective date) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1050[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon OpenSearch Serverless** | Vector and lexical retrieval index backing each Knowledge Base |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1051[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Bedrock Guardrails** | Content filtering for diagnosis-attempted, treatment-recommendation-attempted (beyond what existing clinicians have ordered), medication-titration-attempted, lab-interpretation-attempted, off-protocol-coordination-instruction, out-of-scope clinical advice |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1052[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Chat handler, input/output screening, identity-and-context loading, escalation routing, integration adapters (HL7 listener, FHIR consumer, claims-feed processor, pharmacy-API consumer, vendor-API consumers), seam-detection-rule engine, care-team reporting, outcome correlation, and tool implementations (coordination_state_retrieve, referral_lifecycle_retrieve, encounter_retrieve, medication_list_reconcile, open_followups_retrieve, seam_flags_retrieve, protocol_retrieve, patient_education_content_retrieve, care_team_alert_propose, patient_action_propose, follow_up_schedule, escalation_propose, provenance_retrieve) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1053[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Transition-of-care orchestration workflows, referral-lifecycle workflows, escalation workflows |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1054[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | Public-facing chat endpoint for web, app, SMS, voice, and email channels |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1055[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS WAF** | Rate limiting, bot detection, common attack patterns |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1056[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | patient-coordination-state, provenance-journal, referral-lifecycle-store, transition-of-care-store, seam-flags-registry, caregiver-access-store, consent-record-store, conversation-state, conversation-metadata, tool-call-ledger, coordination-decision-record-journal, care-team-alert-queue, engagement-schedule |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1057[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Coordination-protocol corpus, patient-education library, conversation archive, decision-record journal, provenance archive, outcome-correlation data |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1058[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS HealthLake** | FHIR-native coordination-data integration (Patient, Encounter, Condition, MedicationRequest, MedicationStatement, Observation, DiagnosticReport, ServiceRequest, CarePlan, AllergyIntolerance, Immunization), HL7 v2 and CDA import, FHIR analytics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1059[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon MSK or Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | HL7 ingestion stream for ADT, ORU, SIU messages |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1060[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Customer-managed encryption keys per data class, with separate keys for sensitive-record categories (42 CFR Part 2, mental-health, HIV, genetic) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1061[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Secrets Manager** | Credentials for external EHRs, HIE, payer-claims systems, pharmacy networks, home-health vendors, lab feeds, scheduling systems, care-team workflow systems, crisis-line integrations, mandatory-reporting-pathway integrations, care-navigation systems |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1062[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Operational metrics (engagement rate, attrition rate, referral-closure rate, transition-of-care-completion rate, medication-reconciliation accuracy, seam-flag-detection rate, seam-flag-resolution rate, integration-coverage-by-source rate, citation-coverage rate, per-cohort slices); alarms |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1063[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS CloudTrail** | API-level audit logging including cross-organizational data-access events |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1064[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Assistant-event bus (patient_enrolled, caregiver_added, conversation_completed, care_event_received, seam_flag_detected, seam_flag_resolved, referral_lifecycle_advanced, transition_of_care_advanced, medication_reconciliation_completed, care_team_alert_generated, escalation_initiated, coordination_decision_recorded, sensitive_disclosure_recorded) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1065[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Pinpoint** | Multi-channel patient and caregiver engagement (SMS, push, email) with delivery-status tracking and per-channel preference enforcement |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1066[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Connect** | Warm-handoff queue for care managers, routing integration for clinically-ambiguous cases |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1067[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose** | Streaming audit and telemetry delivery |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1068[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue Data Catalog + Amazon Athena** | SQL access to audit, decision-record, provenance, seam-flags, referral-lifecycle, and telemetry data |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1069[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker (where used)** | Hosted custom seam-detection model inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1070[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Clinical, operational, and outcome dashboards |
