[49m[38;5;10m+    2330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. A production deployment needs to close several gaps that are intentionally out of scope for a recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational data integration as multi-quarter engineering investment.** The integration layer (HL7 listeners, FHIR consumers, claims-feed processors, pharmacy-data integrations, HIE participation, TEFCA QHIN access, vendor-API integrations) is the largest single engineering investment for production deployment. Each integration partner has its own credentials, rate limits, schema variations, identifier conventions, and data-quality issues. The institutional integration-engineering team is named, sized, and committed for the multi-quarter work; without this commitment, the assistant is an interesting prototype operating on partial data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-protocol-corpus governance with full clinical-leadership signoff.** The coordination-protocol corpus (transition-of-care protocols per setting, referral-tracking protocols per specialty, medication-reconciliation protocols, condition-specific coordination playbooks) is the single largest pre-deployment clinical investment. Each protocol is owned by a named clinical leader (patient safety officer, pharmacy director, care-management director, post-discharge care coordinator director, etc.), has an effective date, has an annual review schedule, and has a version history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Seam-detection-rule-engine governance with named clinical-leadership ownership per rule.** Each seam-detection rule (medication discrepancy, referral non-scheduling, transition-of-care incompleteness, test-result acknowledgement gap, conflicting orders, care-plan-item aging, lapsed coverage, etc.) has named clinical-leadership ownership, an effective date, a version history, and a sign-off record. False-positive rates are reviewed per rule with rebalancing decisions made by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Provenance-as-architectural-primitive with audit discipline.** Every entry in the coordination state has a recorded provenance chain. The provenance journal is separately retained, audit-friendly, and reviewable. The assistant's assertions about the patient's care state cite provenance, and the citation chain is preserved across the data lifecycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational consent posture with state-specific variations.** Consent is tracked per data source and per sharing relationship, respects patient preferences, accommodates state-specific privacy regulations (mental-health, HIV, substance-use, genetic, adolescent-confidential), and is operationally enforced through the integration and conversation layers. Counsel familiar with state-specific privacy regulations and with the Information Blocking rule reviews the posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver-as-first-class-participant identity model with state-specific proxy-access rules.** Caregivers have separate identities, separate authentication, separate consent posture, separate message templates, separate burden monitoring, and separate state-law access rules. Per-state caregiver-proxy-access rules vary; counsel reviews the per-state implementation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management-program integration with named clinical-leadership ownership.** The assistant complements existing nurse care managers, complex-case managers, and social workers; the relationship is designed jointly with care-management leadership. The assistant feeds signals to care management about cases that should be promoted into their workload.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort monitoring with launch-gate discipline.** Engagement, attrition, referral-closure, transition-of-care-completion, medication-reconciliation accuracy, seam-detection rate, citation-coverage, scope-violation, and outcome metrics vary by language, channel, condition mix, age cohort, sex, social-determinant flags, caregiver presence, and integration-coverage band. Per-cohort dashboards reviewed by clinical leadership, operations, compliance, regulatory, and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline as multi-quarter to multi-year post-launch commitment.** The pipeline pulls subsequent encounter records, utilization records (admissions, ED visits), referral-closure data, transition-of-care closure data, medication-reconciliation accuracy, and patient-and-caregiver-reported coordination experience. Coordination outcome attribution is harder than chronic-disease attribution because the effects are diffuse and confounded; the analysis is observational rather than causal, with multi-window correlation (30-day, 90-day, 12-month, 24-month) and per-cohort analysis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment with validated translations.** Per-language asset development includes validated coordination-protocol translations, validated patient-education translations, validated regulatory-disclaimer translations, per-language tone calibration, per-language asset versioning, and per-language equity monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology with cross-organizational graceful degradation.** When the integration layer, the protocol corpus, the coordination-state store, or any escalation pathway is unreachable, the assistant degrades gracefully. Per-source failover is documented and tested quarterly. The minimum behavior is "I'm having trouble pulling that data right now; for anything urgent please contact your care team at [number]."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation operations for inappropriate responses.** When a patient or caregiver disputes a bot response, when a clinician flags a coordination decision as wrong, or when a care-management leader identifies a pattern of off-protocol responses, the operations team reproduces the conversation, retrieves cited content and provenance, and either confirms the assistant followed protocol or identifies the deviation and feeds the failure mode into the improvement loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy artifact with regulatory-counsel review.** Where the assistant produces clinical recommendations beyond what existing clinicians have ordered, the FDA SaMD line is in scope. The institutional regulatory positioning is documented, reviewed by FDA-experienced regulatory counsel, and maintained as the deployment evolves.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy rigor.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination platforms with FHIR integration, claims-feed processing, transition-of-care workflows, and (in some cases) hybrid-coordination workforces. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for the cross-organizational integration substrate (HIE participation, TEFCA QHIN access, claims-feed plumbing), and integrate with the institution's care-management, telehealth, and clinical-record infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational ownership across multiple teams.** The assistant sits at the intersection of clinical leadership (multiple specialties), care management, the licensed-clinician workforce, compliance, regulatory, IT, the call center, patient experience, the malpractice carrier, and (in some institutions) the equity and patient-advocacy office. Without named ownership for each team's slice, deployment falters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Promote integration-coverage-tracking-per-patient to architectural primitive. Per-patient integration coverage is computed from the registered network and the active integration partnerships, with per-source coverage status (live, intermittent, paused, never-integrated). Integration-coverage band drives per-patient assistant confidence and per-cohort monitoring. Sustained-coverage-degradation triggers ops alerts and (where degradation is structural) protocol-corpus tuning. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Specify per-content-version-stamping on every coordination-decision-record so that audit can reproduce the protocol-corpus version, the patient-education-library version, the seam-detection-rule version, the prompt version, and the model version active at the time of decision. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
