[49m[38;5;10m+    2446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Post-discharge readmission-prevention coordinator.** A focused variant for the post-discharge window after hospitalization, with discharge-instruction reinforcement, medication-reconciliation surfacing, follow-up-appointment validation, condition-specific symptom monitoring (heart failure weight tracking; COPD symptom check; sepsis-recovery monitoring), and aggressive readmission-prevention escalation. Frequently the first variant institutions deploy because the readmission outcome is the most directly attributable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Oncology-care-coordination assistant.** A focused variant for active oncology treatment, with treatment-course milestone tracking, infusion-schedule coordination, side-effect symptom-tracking with oncology-team escalation, supportive-care service navigation (palliative care, social work, financial navigation, integrative oncology), and tight integration with the oncology nurse-navigator workforce. Typically the most resource-intensive coordination context per patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transplant-care-coordination assistant.** A focused variant for solid-organ-transplant recipients, with immunosuppression-medication management coordination, lab-monitoring schedule coordination, infection-monitoring, transplant-team contact orchestration, and tight integration with the transplant program's nurse coordinators. Lifelong relationship; high stakes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Maternal-care-coordination assistant.** A focused variant for the perinatal and postpartum period, with prenatal-visit coordination, gestational-diabetes management coordination, postpartum-visit coordination, postpartum-mental-health screening (with mental-health-bot pathway from recipe 11.8), newborn-pediatric-coordination, and integration with maternal-fetal-medicine specialists for high-risk pregnancies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pediatric-complex-care coordinator.** A focused variant for pediatric patients with medical complexity (multiple specialists, durable medical equipment, home-nursing services, school-coordination, transition-to-adult-care planning), with explicit caregiver-as-primary-participant identity model, parent-or-guardian consent posture, and integration with the medical home and the school-nursing services.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Palliative-and-end-of-life-care coordinator.** A focused variant for serious-illness and end-of-life care, with goals-of-care-conversation coordination, symptom-management coordination, hospice-eligibility assessment support, family-meeting coordination, and tight integration with the palliative-care team. Sensitive domain requiring particular care with caregiver bereavement and team workforce coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Behavioral-health-care coordinator.** A focused variant for patients with serious mental illness, with psychiatric medication-coordination, therapy-appointment coordination, case-management coordination, integration with community-mental-health centers, and tight integration with the patient's psychiatrist and therapist. Often runs in parallel with recipe 11.8 (mental-health support bot).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-in-Medicare-Advantage-population.** A variant calibrated to MA member populations, with Star-rating measure coordination (medication adherence, follow-up after hospitalization, care-for-older-adults), HEDIS-measure-driven coordination, and tight integration with the payer's care-management program. The MA contractual and reporting context drives the protocol design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-in-Medicaid-population.** A variant calibrated to Medicaid populations, with social-determinant-of-health screening, integrated care-coordination across medical and behavioral-health and social-services, transportation-coordination, and integration with state-specific Medicaid managed-care reporting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-for-Veterans.** A variant deployed through the VA or partnering community-care providers, with VA-EHR integration, community-care referral coordination, mental-health-and-PTSD coordination (with mental-health-bot pathway from recipe 11.8), substance-use coordination (with 42 CFR Part 2 compliance), and integration with the VA care-management workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-for-employer-population.** A variant deployed through employer-benefits, with employer-privacy walls (the employer cannot access individual usage or content), workplace-specific coordination considerations (work-schedule coordination for appointments), and integration with the employer's EAP, occupational health, and care-navigation benefits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-for-rural-or-frontier-populations.** A variant calibrated to rural and frontier patient populations, with telehealth-coordination prominence, transportation-barrier prominence, multi-specialty-distance coordination, and integration with rural-health-clinic and critical-access-hospital systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment beyond English plus Spanish.** Per-language asset development reviewed by clinical leadership and language-services teams, with per-language equity monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Voice-channel-deployment.** A voice-channel variant for patients without smartphones, patients with disabilities affecting written communication, patients in older-adult cohorts, patients who prefer voice. Voice-specific design includes slower pacing, briefer responses, and accessibility considerations. Crisis-pathway and escalation integrity are preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-licensed-coordinator deployment.** The assistant handles routine engagement; a licensed care manager is available for complex coordination beyond the assistant's scope. The architectural extension is the licensed-coordinator scheduling and case-load management, plus the differentiation between assistant-scope and coordinator-scope topics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous-improvement loop with structured failure-mode labeling.** Beyond per-conversation feedback, the institution runs a structured labeling program where reviewers (RNs, care managers, clinical leadership) tag failure modes (out-of-scope, off-protocol, seam-detection-miss, seam-detection-false-positive, citation-gap, provenance-gap, scope-violation, equity-disparity). The labels feed the protocol-corpus, seam-detection-rule, prompt-tuning, and policy-revision workflows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Provider-network optimization overlay.** The assistant's data on referral-closure rates, scheduling barriers, and patient-satisfaction with specialty referrals feeds the institution's provider-network design and contracting strategy, with appropriate privacy controls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Population-health overlay.** The assistant's outputs feed an institutional population-health dashboard tracking patterns of coordination across the population for quality-measurement, clinical-program-design, and value-based-contract reporting purposes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordination-for-clinical-trial-participants.** A variant specifically for patients enrolled in clinical trials, with study-protocol coordination, study-visit coordination, study-team integration, and adverse-event surfacing. Subject to additional regulatory considerations (clinical trial regulations, IRB protocols, sponsor-data-sharing rules).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-mediated-data-exchange variant for unaffiliated organizations.** Where the institution does not have direct integration with one of the patient's clinical organizations, the patient can authorize data access through SMART on FHIR apps using the certified patient-facing APIs from each organization. The variant uses patient-mediated exchange as the integration path, with explicit handling of the latency and completeness differences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-payer-coordination-for-dual-eligible patients.** A variant specifically for dual-eligible (Medicare and Medicaid) patients, with cross-payer-claims integration, dual-special-needs-plan coordination protocols, and integration with both Medicare and Medicaid care-management programs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Population-health-equity overlay.** The assistant's per-cohort metrics are reviewed monthly by an equity committee with explicit threshold criteria for cohort disparities; rules and protocols are re-tuned to close disparities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.1 (FAQ Chatbot):** Same chapter, foundational. The coordination assistant inherits the input-screening pipeline, scope filtering, conversation logging, audit pattern, persona discipline, and per-cohort monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.2 (Appointment Scheduling Bot):** Same chapter. Scheduling actions surfaced by the coordination assistant route to the scheduling bot's booking infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.3 (Prescription Refill Request Bot):** Same chapter. Refill needs surfaced during coordination route to the refill workflow; medication-coordination is in scope but medication-refill-execution is out of scope and routes here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.4 (Pre-Visit Intake Bot):** Same chapter. The coordination assistant's longitudinal context can pre-populate intake for upcoming visits with consent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.5 (Insurance Benefits Navigator):** Same chapter. Benefits questions surfaced during coordination route to the benefits navigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.6 (Symptom Checker / Triage Bot):** Same chapter. Acute-symptom presentations during coordination conversations route to the triage workflow with the coordination context preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.7 (Chronic Disease Management Coach):** Same chapter. Patients with chronic conditions may have both deployments; the coach helps the patient manage their conditions while the coordinator helps the patient navigate their providers. Cross-product integration is valuable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.8 (Mental Health Support Bot):** Same chapter. Mental-health concerns surfaced during coordination route to the mental-health bot pathway; many multi-condition patients have both deployments with consent-gated context sharing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.5 (Cross-Facility Patient Matching):** Chapter 5. The coordination assistant depends on cross-facility patient matching to identify the same patient across data sources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.7 (Longitudinal Patient Matching):** Chapter 5. Long-term coordination relationships need longitudinal matching across name changes and identifier changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.8 (Privacy-Preserving Record Linkage):** Chapter 5. Where direct identifier sharing is constrained, privacy-preserving record linkage is the mechanism.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.9 (National-Scale Patient Matching, TEFCA):** Chapter 5. National-scale patient matching enables cross-organizational coordination at scale through the TEFCA framework.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 2.5 (After-Visit Summary Generation):** Chapter 2. After-visit summaries feed the coordination assistant's longitudinal context and the patient-facing context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 2.6 (Clinical Note Summarization):** Chapter 2. Clinical-note summarization powers the coordination assistant's encounter-context-summary tool.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 2.9 (Clinical Decision Support Synthesis):** Chapter 2. Where coordination conversations require synthesizing complex clinical context, the synthesis pattern from this recipe is reused.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 3.7 (Patient Deterioration Early Warning):** Chapter 3. Coordination-specific deterioration patterns (transition-of-care decline, post-discharge decompensation) complement clinical-side detection systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 3.8 (Readmission Risk Anomaly Detection):** Chapter 3. Readmission-risk anomaly signals inform coordination intensity and care-team-attention prioritization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 4.5 (Medication Adherence Intervention Targeting):** Chapter 4. The coordination assistant's medication-adherence support builds on adherence-intervention targeting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 4.6 (Care Gap Prioritization):** Chapter 4. Care-gap signals feed the coordination assistant's seam-detection-rule prioritization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 4.7 (Care Management Program Enrollment):** Chapter 4. Patients identified as appropriate for care management may receive coordination-assistant support as part of their program.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 4.9 (Personalized Care Plan Generation):** Chapter 4. Personalized care plans drive the coordination protocol selection per patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.1+ (Predictive Analytics, Chapter 7):** Risk scores including readmission-risk and ED-utilization-risk prediction inform coordination intensity and seam-flag-detection prioritization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 10.5 (Patient-Facing Voice Assistant):** Chapter 10. Voice-channel coordination builds on voice-assistant ASR/TTS patterns with crisis-pathway and escalation integrity preserved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.x (Time Series Analysis, Chapter 12):** Coordination-state-trajectory analysis (e.g., re-engagement-rate trends, post-discharge symptom trajectories) benefits from time-series patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 13.x (Knowledge Graphs, Chapter 13):** Coordination relationships between patients, providers, organizations, encounters, referrals, and care events have natural graph structure; knowledge-graph patterns may complement the structured-state architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
